Perimeter Defense - Email Security > [T4]: Mail Server Hardening: DISA & CIS


Email security would not be complete without discussing mail server security. Most attacks target users to get an initial foothold inside the network and acquire more valuable targets, such as the mailbox server, the crown jewels attackers run after. Mailbox servers are very appealing targets for attackers because they are where organizations' emails are stored.

 

Hardening a mailbox server is a broad topic beyond the scope of this course. However, there are public security guides created by established organizations on security best practices for mailbox servers.

 

The U.S Department of Defense (DOD) has many security hardening guides published by Defense Information Systems Agency (DISA). The Defense Information Systems Agency (DISA) is a combat support agency that provides IT and communication support to all institutes and individuals working for the U.S. Department of Defense. DISA oversees the IT/technological aspect of organizing, delivering, and managing defense-related information.

DoD security hardening guides, also known as STIGs (Security Technical Implementation Guide), provide best security practices for different technologies. STIGs are published in XSL format and require a special tool to view them or can be viewed online at https://www.stigviewer.com/. There are currently 512 published hardening guides for different technologies such as ActiveDirectory, routers, firewalls, databases, and servers of different types. 

 

Microsoft Exchange is the most popular mailbox server. The latest published guide for Exchange servers is Microsoft Exchange 2016 Mailbox Server Security Technical Implementation Guide and can be viewed at https://www.stigviewer.com/stig/microsoft_exchange_2016_mailbox_server/. You can also download it as an Excel file from the same page.

 

Figure - zoom in


For a single guide, DISA offers different hardening profiles based on the targeted level of security. As we can see inside the red rectangular, there are three categories; classified, public, and sensitive systems. Clicking on each profile will view the corresponding profile. Its up to organizations to determine the hardening level that works for them. For example, military organizations should have a higher security level than traditional businesses. The most important thing to remember is that security should be a business enabler, and extra lock-down may disrupt operations. Finding the right balance between security and business is the key to smooth operations.

Regardless of the selected profile, Organizations should try to implement at least High and Medium Severity controls. I noticed that most high and medium controls could be implemented safely across most organizations. In the above example, we see one high severity control: email-aware virus protection.

 

Figure - zoom in

 

Another well-known security hardening guides are CIS benchmarks. CIS Benchmarks are best practices for the secure configuration of a target system. They are developed through a unique consensus-based process comprised of cybersecurity professionals and subject matter experts worldwide.

Like DISA STIGs, there is a hardening guide for Microsoft Exchange 2016, and here we can see a list of recommended security configurations for mailbox servers.

 

Figure - zoom in

 

Each control has more details about how to configure it:

 

Figure - zoom in

 

Most CIS Benchmarks include multiple configuration profiles. The Level 1 profile is considered a base recommendation that can be implemented promptly and is designed not to have an extensive performance impact. The Level 1 profile benchmark intends to lower your organization's attack surface while keeping machines usable without hindering business functionality.

 

The Level 2 profile is considered "defense in depth" and is intended for environments where security is paramount. The recommendations associated with the Level 2 profile can have an adverse effect on your organization if not implemented appropriately or without due care.

 

From personal experience, I found CIS benchmarks easier to implement because they are more detailed and fit most businesses. Unlike DISA STIGS, which are somehow restrictive.

 

After implementing CIS or DISA STIGs, we need a way to verify that the configurations we implemented have been applied correctly. That may be a painful manual task. Luckily, there are automated tools security engineers can use to audit a server's security compliance against DISA STIGs and CIS benchmarks. For example, the Nessus vulnerability scanner has a compliance audit feature that can audit a server against a particular DISA STIG or CIS benchmark.


Spending enough time researching which hardening guide works better for your organization's business needs is crucial. As a security team, our objective is to achieve the highest POSSIBLE level of security without interrupting operations. It's fine to skip some controls during the hardening process. Remember...whatever can't be gained in its entirety should not be discarded entirely. 

 

Security teams should work closely in a cooperative and friendly atmosphere with system administrators to ensure operations will not be impacted when deploying new controls. Do not just ask them to do it; instead, work with them and provide the highest level of help to remove the traditional Security V.s IT tension involved in these situations.
 

At the end of this lesson, I would like to highlight the importance of using DISA STIGs and CIS benchmarks to harden other technologies such as network devices, desktop machines, servers, and system/network services. Having a well-defined security baseline makes it easier for security teams to measure progress at different intervals and maintain layered defenses.

 

Although threats targeting email servers are not that popular, they have a destructive impact. Here is a real intrusion for an Exchange server that results in many devastating actions, such as exposing all user's credentials (credentials dumping).
